    biography: 'Rajmund Kolbe was a Polish Conventual Franciscan friar who founded a highly productive religious publishing apostolate — the City of the Immaculata near Warsaw. When Germany invaded Poland, he sheltered 3,000 Jews and Polish refugees. Arrested and sent to Auschwitz, when a prisoner escaped and the Nazis selected 10 men to die of starvation in reprisal, Maximilian stepped forward to take the place of a young father named Franciszek Gajowniczek. He outlasted all the others in the starvation bunker and was killed by lethal injection on August 14, 1941.',
    pathToSainthood: 'Beatified in 1971, canonized by Pope John Paul II on October 10, 1982 as a "martyr of charity." Franciszek Gajowniczek, the man whose place he took, attended the canonization.',
    miracles: [
      'Healing miracles verified for his canonization',
      'His act of charity in Auschwitz described by Pope John Paul II as the greatest act of charity since Christ',
    ],
    martyrdom: 'Killed by lethal carbolic acid injection in the starvation bunker of Auschwitz-Birkenau on August 14, 1941.',
