    summary: 'The pilgrim Pope who helped end Communism, survived assassination, and forgave his shooter.',
    biography: 'Karol Józef Wojtyła grew up in Poland under Nazi and then Soviet occupation, lost his entire immediate family before reaching adulthood, and was ordained a priest and later bishop clandestinely under Communist oppression. Elected Pope in 1978 as the first non-Italian Pope in 455 years, his 26-year pontificate was one of the longest in history. He traveled more than any Pope in history, visiting 129 countries. His support of the Solidarity movement in Poland helped bring about the peaceful collapse of Communist rule in Eastern Europe. He survived an assassination attempt in 1981 and visited his shooter in prison to personally forgive him. He canonized more saints than all previous popes combined.',
    pathToSainthood: 'Beatified by Pope Benedict XVI on May 1, 2011 — the fastest beatification in modern history. Canonized by Pope Francis on April 27, 2014.',
