    summary: 'Albanian-Indian nun who cared for the poorest of the poor in Calcutta, Nobel Peace Prize laureate.',
    biography: 'Anjezë Gonxhe Bojaxhiu was born in Skopje (modern North Macedonia) to an Albanian family. She joined the Sisters of Loreto and taught at a school in Calcutta. In 1946, on a train journey, she received what she called her "call within a call" — Christ asking her to leave the convent to serve the poorest of the poor. She founded the Missionaries of Charity, whose members take a fourth vow: "wholehearted free service to the poorest of the poor." She cared for lepers, the dying, orphans, and the destitute of Calcutta for decades, and was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 1979.',
