    summary: 'Capuchin friar who bore the stigmata for 50 years, billocated, and read souls in confession.',
    biography: 'Francesco Forgione from Pietrelcina, Italy, entered the Capuchin Franciscans and was ordained a priest in 1910. In 1918 he received the visible stigmata — the wounds of Christ — which he bore for 50 years until they disappeared at his death, leaving his skin completely healed. He spent up to 15 hours a day in the confessional and became one of the most sought-after spiritual directors of the 20th century. The extraordinary mystical phenomena surrounding him — bilocation, reading of souls, healing miracles, and fragrance of flowers from his wounds — made him both celebrated and controversial during his lifetime.',
