    summary: 'Aztec convert to whom Our Lady of Guadalupe appeared, leaving her image on his tilma.',
    biography: 'Cuauhtlatoatzin (Talking Eagle) was an indigenous Nahua peasant who converted to Christianity and took the name Juan Diego after the Spanish conquest of Mexico. In December 1531, the Virgin Mary appeared to him four times on Tepeyac Hill, asking that a shrine be built there. To convince the skeptical bishop, the Virgin instructed Juan Diego to gather roses in December — miraculously blooming in winter — and when he opened his tilma (cloak) before the bishop, her image was miraculously imprinted on it. The image of Our Lady of Guadalupe has been scientifically studied and cannot be explained — no paint is used and the image has the properties of a living human eye.',
